=========================================
C++ SET (Associative Container)
INTERVIEW PREPARATION NOTES
=========================================

1. What is set?
---------------

std::set is an STL associative container that stores unique elements in sorted order.

Characteristics:
✓ Unique elements only
✓ Automatically sorted
✓ Implemented using Red-Black Tree
✓ No duplicate values

Example:

set<int> s;

s.insert(30);
s.insert(10);
s.insert(20);
s.insert(10);

Output:

10 20 30

Duplicate 10 is ignored.

-----------------------------------------

2. Why Use set?
---------------

Need:
✓ Unique elements
✓ Automatic sorting
✓ Fast search

Without set:

vector<int> v;

Need:
- Manual sorting
- Duplicate checking

set does both automatically.

-----------------------------------------

3. Internal Implementation
--------------------------

Implemented using:

Red-Black Tree
(Self-Balancing Binary Search Tree)

Example:

Insert:

30 10 20

Tree:

      20
     /  \
   10    30

Height remains balanced.

Interview Answer:
std::set is implemented using a self-balancing Red-Black Tree.

-----------------------------------------

4. Why is set Sorted?
---------------------

Elements are stored according to tree ordering.

Example:

Insert:

50
10
30
20

Output:

10 20 30 50

Regardless of insertion order.

-----------------------------------------

5. Why are Duplicates Not Allowed?
----------------------------------

set stores unique keys.

Example:

s.insert(10);
s.insert(10);
s.insert(10);

Result:

10

Only one copy stored.

-----------------------------------------

6. Complexity
-------------

insert()        O(log n)
erase()         O(log n)
find()          O(log n)
count()         O(log n)

begin()         O(1)
end()           O(1)

size()          O(1)
empty()         O(1)

-----------------------------------------

7. Why is insert() O(log n)?
----------------------------

Because insertion happens in a balanced tree.

Maximum tree height:

log n

Therefore:

insert() = O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

8. Why is find() O(log n)?
--------------------------

Search follows BST path.

Example:

       40
      /  \
    20    60
   / \
 10  30

Searching 30:

40 -> 20 -> 30

Height:

log n

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

9. Why No Random Access?
------------------------

Not stored contiguously.

Not supported:

s[0];

Error.

Reason:

Tree-based structure.

Interview Answer:
set does not support random access because elements are stored in a tree, not an array.

-----------------------------------------

10. Iterator Stability
----------------------

Insert:

Existing iterators remain valid.

Erase:

Only erased iterator becomes invalid.

Interview Answer:
set provides stable iterators because tree nodes are not moved during insertion.

-----------------------------------------

11. Common Functions
--------------------

insert()
erase()

find()
count()

begin()
end()

