-----------------------------------------

12. find()
-----------

Returns iterator.

Example:

auto it = s.find(20);

if(it != s.end())
{
    cout << "Found";
}

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

13. count()
------------

Checks existence.

Returns:

0 or 1

Example:

s.count(20);

Because duplicates are not allowed.

-----------------------------------------

14. lower_bound()
-----------------

Returns first element >= key.

Example:

set:

10 20 30 40

lower_bound(25)

Returns:

30

-----------------------------------------

15. upper_bound()
-----------------

Returns first element > key.

Example:

set:

10 20 30 40

upper_bound(30)

Returns:

40

-----------------------------------------

16. erase()
------------

Delete element.

Example:

s.erase(20);

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

17. set vs vector
-----------------

vector
------
Duplicates allowed
Unsorted
Search O(n)

set
---
Unique elements
Sorted
Search O(log n)

Interview Answer:
Use set when uniqueness and sorted order are required.

-----------------------------------------

18. set vs unordered_set
------------------------

set
---
Red-Black Tree
Sorted
O(log n)

unordered_set
-------------
Hash Table
Unsorted
Average O(1)

Interview Answer:
Use set when sorted order is needed. Use unordered_set for fastest lookup.

-----------------------------------------

19. When to Use set?
--------------------

Use set when:

✓ Unique elements required
✓ Sorted order required
✓ Fast search required

Examples:

- Remove duplicates
- Ordered data
- Range queries
- Competitive programming

